<font color="#FF0000">WAR-MEDALS</font><br>
<tt>Mon Feb 24 18:21:48 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hey Doc:<br>
     I can see your point of view-thanks for posing it and clearing up any confusion.  In the future just try to pose them in a more sincere tone, it is possibly in anger (This war breeds it) to misread or misunderstand a post.  In regards to your points on valor-I agree with your position in regards to saving lives.  I do disagree on your machine gun nest example though, let me explain why.  First, bear in mind this is my perception from my little corner of the war.<br>
In regards to invading their country, I had nothing to do with policy (if I did there would have been no fight), I was just taken by Uncle Sam and sent over there.  I can understand the will of the Vietnamese people to fight, what they perceived as a US invasion, aggression, or whatever colorful adjective you would like to call it.  When you are actually there and on the ground, in the mud, sweating, and eduring, war (all wars) have a habit of becoming less political, ideological, or moral.  War becomes sheer survival.  To wipe out that machine gun means the difference betweem life and death-the instinct to survive.  The military establishment accepts these acts as measures of its job (To kill people and destroy things).  Fighting for the average soldier (both sides) is not a medal seeking journey, its a fight to survive, to come home.  Talk to most combat vets, they will have a earned respect (maybe not like) for the enemy who edures like themselves.  In regards to medals for as you call &quot;killing&quot;, look at the circumstances and you will find out that it involves about 99% survival.  It is easy now to call Nam a invasion, but to most of us vets, it was &quot;let's get this over with, so I can get the hell out of here&quot;, with our leaders placing us in their country.  Last point-Are there guys that seek medals or try to pursue their actions to earn a medal??  OF COURSE!  At least in my unit, NO ONE and I mean NO ONE was there to kill (Like a commie for Christ, Mommy or anyone else) for a Bronze Star, Silver Star or Medal of Honor.  Just remember Doc-most killing in war is part of the old slogan-&quot;Kill or be killed&quot;.  Think about it.  In regards to innocent peasants, I really feel for those peasants who were caught in a war, amongst VC they feared, a South Vietnamese gov't they disliked and US forces.  My unit tried all it could to build schools and villages and to take care of them.  The average guy doesn't make any policy-just follows (NO not like a dog-there is no choice).  Our government put us in a war, where the enemy started out as VC from local villages we were sent to protect. a HORRIBLE prospect that never should have happen but did.  Remember this too, that some so-called peasants where also making devasting booby traps and planting them (Women-Men and children).  The nature of war in Nam was confused to say the least.  This is my point of you.  I wear medals for as you call &quot;killing the enemy&quot;, and I can assure you they were for my survival and the survival of my friends.  I take no pleasure in killing anyone, but will do so to protect my life and those I care about (that survival thing).  I will wear those medals with pride too, I did what I had to be here today.  The fustration shouldn't be with the soldier, but with the leaders and politicians that created that mess.  You know that Doc.  People die in war-all people-that's the way it is (has been-always will be).  All the more reason why our generation needs to see that our children never have to fight in a war, unless it is to directly protect themselves and their families.  By the way thanks for the welcome.
<p><code>--   (Prophet) </code><p>


